Not the least misfortune of Maecenas was his marriage to a woman whom he could neither live with nor without -separating from and returning to her so often, that, according to Seneca, he was a thousand times married, yet never had but one wife. Friends he had many, loyal and devoted friendS, on whose society and sym- pathy he leant more and more as the years wore on. He rarely stirred from Rome, loving its smoke, its thronged and noisy streetS‚ its whirl of human passionS, as Johnson loved Fleet Street, or “the sweet shady side of Pall Mall,'’ better than all the verdure of Tivoli, or the soft airs and exquisite scenery of Baiae.
